{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565842","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565842"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:33:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:33:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18520"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18520","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18520"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.11,0.1,0.11,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100898"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18520"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83323"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4670"},{"type":"tags","id":"4925"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26805"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27379"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100898"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old transgender man presents to the General Practice clinic with his two-week-old infant. He gave birth vaginally after an uncomplicated pregnancy during which he temporarily discontinued testosterone therapy. He has not had chest reconstructive surgery. He expresses a desire to chestfeed but is concerned about resuming testosterone. He has no significant medical history apart from gender dysphoria and takes no regular medications currently. On examination, both he and the infant appear well with vital signs within normal limits. The infant is gaining weight appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue without testosterone while chestfeeding","Resume testosterone with concurrent chestfeeding","Commence formula feeding only","Start microdosing testosterone while chestfeeding","Alternate between formula and chestfeeding"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a transgender man who wishes to chestfeed his newborn infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue without testosterone while chestfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan, as it aligns with the parent\u0027s preference and ensures the safety of the infant. Testosterone therapy can suppress milk production and may transfer into breast milk, potentially affecting the infant\u0027s growth and development. Although data is limited, current guidelines recommend avoiding testosterone during chestfeeding. Chestfeeding provides significant nutritional and immunological benefits for the infant while fostering emotional bonding with the parent. Supporting the parent in their desire to chestfeed is essential, especially when there is no medical contraindication. Guidelines from the Royal Women\u0027s Hospital Pregnancy and Breastfeeding Medicines Guidelines and the Australian Medicines Handbook emphasize avoiding testosterone during this period, though specific guidance from RANZCOG is lacking. Management should include lactation support, regular monitoring of both parent and infant, and a plan to safely resume testosterone therapy after chestfeeding ends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResume testosterone with concurrent chestfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as testosterone would likely suppress milk production and could potentially expose the infant to testosterone through breast milk, which may affect the infant\u0027s development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence formula feeding only\u003C/strong\u003E would unnecessarily deprive both parent and infant of the benefits of chestfeeding when there is no medical contraindication and the parent has expressed a desire to chestfeed. There is also no evidence that changing the feeding method is required as the parent appears well and the infant is appropriately gaining weight. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart microdosing testosterone while chestfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended despite being a practice adopted by some transgender individuals. Even at lower doses, testosterone can still suppress milk production and potentially transfer to the infant through breast milk. While microdosing (using a lower dose or intermittent testosterone) is sometimes used by transgender individuals to achieve more gradual masculinization effects, there is insufficient evidence regarding its safety during chestfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlternate between formula and chestfeeding\u003C/strong\u003E would likely compromise milk supply as regular breast stimulation is needed to maintain adequate production. This approach could lead to premature cessation of chestfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement should include referral to a lactation consultant familiar with gender-diverse parents, ongoing mental health support, and regular monitoring of both parent and infant wellbeing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Testosterone therapy should be discontinued during pregnancy and chestfeeding to maintain milk production and avoid infant exposure.","Chestfeeding is possible and safe for transgender men who have not had chest reconstructive surgery.","Support from lactation consultants and mental health professionals is essential for transgender parents who choose to chestfeed."],"references":["Royal Women\u0027s Hospital. Pregnancy and breastfeeding medicines guidelines. Available at: https://thewomens.rwh.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook. Available at: https://amhonline.amh.net.au","Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Guidelines. Available at: https://ranzcog.edu.au","Klein B, Greenberg J, Cordero A, et al. Chestfeeding and lactation for transgender men: A review of the literature. Transgend Health. 2019;4(1):125-132 Available at: https://www.liebertpub.com/doi/10.1089/trgh.2018.0077","Murray SF, Rush N, and Dovey S. A review of lactation and breastfeeding in transgender men: Addressing health and societal barriers. J Human Lactation. 2021;37(1):16-25. Available at: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/0890334420965153"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83323"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18520"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83323"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-27T23:15:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T12:40:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11249"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100898"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attribut